{"cursor":"12038","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, a 'nuclear space' is a topological vector space with many of the\ngood properties of finite-dimensional vector spaces. The topology on them can be\ndefined by a family of seminorms whose unit balls decrease rapidly in size.\nVector spaces whose elements are \"smooth\" in some sense tend to be nuclear\nspaces; a typical example of a nuclear space is the set of smooth functions on a\ncompact manifold. Although important, nuclear spaces are not widely used,\npossibly because the definition is notoriously difficult to understand.\n\nMuch of the theory of nuclear spaces was developed by Alexander Grothendieck and\npublished in .\n","linknr":152,"url":"Nuclear_space","recorded":1362512615,"links":13,"instances":["mathematics"],"pdf":["http://www.math.uni-paderborn.de/~johansen/seminars/minlos.pdf"],"categories":["Operator theory","Topological vector spaces"],"headings":["Definition","Examples","Properties","Bochner–Minlos theorem","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/9/9/3994ef79ba3f30059495b903432bbcf6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/5/6/a56b142191daaecbc491fdaf7ad4fb16.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/6/f/86f93d33fd9d0e70a4106dc97d74cace.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/3/4/e34164fcbe471b92c400da47ce97a486.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/7/2/b72bb92668acc30b4474caff40274044.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/7/a/37a12b78a9ca96989ad7ceceacb37ea2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/5/e/45e18329bd29c65c17f40a3d519cadd6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/b/5/7b593a47d7117953ba199f4c6e715c5c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/e/4/1e427cff05fd939a639e1fd2a2244076.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/d/7/bd79027c6a081d4dc2f2b5eeb42e19c7.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_8